h1. Linux Terminal Environment Setup Guide

{toc}

{info}
This guide walks through setting up a modern, productive Linux terminal environment from scratch. It covers Fish shell, Ghostty terminal, tmux, Neovim, Starship prompt, Yazi file manager, and Volta (Node.js version manager). Target audience: developers setting up a new Linux machine.
{info}

----

h2. 1. Fish Shell

Fish is a smart, user-friendly command line shell with features like autosuggestions, syntax highlighting, and tab completions that work out of the box.

h3. Installation

{note}
On Ubuntu/Debian, the default apt repository may ship an outdated version of Fish. Add the official PPA first.
{note}

*Ubuntu/Debian (with PPA):*
{code:language=bash}
sudo apt-add-repository ppa:fish-shell/release-3
sudo apt update
sudo apt install fish
{code}

*Arch Linux:*
{code:language=bash}
sudo pacman -S fish
{code}

*Fedora:*
{code:language=bash}
sudo dnf install fish
{code}

h3. Set Fish as Default Shell

{code:language=bash}
# Add fish to the list of valid login shells
echo $(which fish) | sudo tee -a /etc/shells

# Change your default shell
chsh -s $(which fish)
{code}

{note}
Log out and back in for the default shell change to take effect.
{note}

h3. Configuration

Fish reads its configuration from {{~/.config/fish/config.fish}}. Create or edit this file with your preferred settings.

A recommended starting configuration:

{code:language=bash}
# ~/.config/fish/config.fish

# Volta (Node.js version manager)
set -gx VOLTA_HOME "$HOME/.volta"
fish_add_path "$VOLTA_HOME/bin"

# Starship prompt
starship init fish | source
{code}

h3. Yazi Shell Wrapper Function

The {{y}} function wraps Yazi so that your working directory follows you when you exit the file manager. Save this as {{~/.config/fish/functions/y.fish}}:

{code:language=bash}
function y
    set tmp (mktemp -t "yazi-cwd.XXXXXX")
    yazi $argv --cwd-file="$tmp"
    if set cwd (command cat -- "$tmp"); and [ -n "$cwd" ]; and [ "$cwd" != "$PWD" ]
        builtin cd -- "$cwd"
    end
    rm -f -- "$tmp"
end
{code}

This lets you launch Yazi by typing {{y}} and have your shell {{cd}} into whatever directory you were browsing when you quit.

h3. Verify

{code:language=bash}
fish --version
{code}

