h2. 4. Neovim

Neovim is a hyperextensible Vim-based text editor. This guide uses [NvChad|https://nvchad.com/] as a starter configuration, which provides LSP support, a plugin manager (lazy.nvim), and a polished default experience.

h3. Installation

{warning}
The version of Neovim in the Ubuntu/Debian {{apt}} repository is frequently outdated. Use the unstable PPA or an AppImage for the latest stable release.
{warning}

*Ubuntu/Debian (PPA — recommended):*
{code:language=bash}
sudo add-apt-repository ppa:neovim-ppa/unstable
sudo apt update
sudo apt install neovim
{code}

*Ubuntu/Debian (AppImage — alternative):*

Download the latest AppImage from [Neovim GitHub Releases|https://github.com/neovim/neovim/releases], then:

{code:language=bash}
chmod +x nvim.appimage
sudo mv nvim.appimage /usr/local/bin/nvim
{code}

*Arch Linux:*
{code:language=bash}
sudo pacman -S neovim
{code}

*Fedora:*
{code:language=bash}
sudo dnf install neovim
{code}

h3. Prerequisites

{code:language=bash}
# Required for Telescope (fuzzy finder) and many LSP workflows
sudo apt install ripgrep

# Build tools required by some plugins (treesitter, etc.)
sudo apt install build-essential
{code}

h3. NvChad Starter Configuration

{code:language=bash}
# Clone the NvChad starter into your Neovim config directory
git clone https://github.com/NvChad/starter ~/.config/nvim

# Launch Neovim — lazy.nvim bootstraps automatically and installs all plugins
nvim
{code}

{info}
On first launch, lazy.nvim will install all configured plugins. This may take a minute. Subsequent launches are fast.
{info}

h3. Installing LSP Servers

Inside Neovim, use Mason to install language servers:

{code:language=none}
:MasonInstall <server-name>

" Examples:
:MasonInstall lua-language-server
:MasonInstall typescript-language-server
:MasonInstall pyright
{code}

Run {{:Mason}} to open the Mason UI and browse all available servers, linters, and formatters.

h3. Verify

{code:language=bash}
nvim --version
{code}

