h2. Linux-Specific Gotchas

* *tmux-yank clipboard:* Requires {{xclip}} (X11) or {{wl-clipboard}} (Wayland). Install with {{sudo apt install xclip}} or {{sudo apt install wl-clipboard}}.
* *Outdated Neovim in apt:* The default Ubuntu/Debian {{apt}} repository ships a very old version of Neovim. Always use the {{neovim-ppa/unstable}} PPA or an AppImage from GitHub Releases.
* *Fish shell PATH:* Volta, Cargo, and other tools that modify {{~/.bashrc}} will not affect Fish automatically. Always add their {{PATH}} entries to {{~/.config/fish/config.fish}} using {{fish_add_path}} or {{set -gx}}.
* *Ghostty binary path in tmux command:* If Ghostty launches before your Fish environment is fully initialized, {{fish}} and {{tmux}} may not be on the {{PATH}}. Use absolute paths (e.g., {{/usr/bin/fish}}, {{/usr/bin/tmux}}) in the Ghostty {{command}} config option to be safe.
* *Rust/Cargo for Yazi:* On distros without a packaged Yazi binary, building from source via Cargo requires a recent Rust toolchain. The {{rustup}} installer handles this cleanly.
* *NvChad first launch:* The initial Neovim launch with NvChad will install many plugins and may appear slow. Subsequent launches will be fast. Ensure you have a working internet connection on first launch.
* *fd-find vs fd:* On Ubuntu/Debian, the {{fd}} binary is installed as {{fdfind}} to avoid a naming conflict. Create a symlink if needed: {{sudo ln -s $(which fdfind) /usr/local/bin/fd}}
